<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 93 / Midland strengthens profits to Pounds 178m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MIDLAND Bank, which was taken over by HSBC Holdings last year, yesterday
disclosed a strong rise in pre-tax profits to Pounds 178m for 1992 against
Pounds 36m for the previous year. Provisions for bad debts fell to Pounds
676m, against Pounds 903m.
Midland's capital ratio strengthened to 10.7 per cent on the retention of
Pounds 102m after tax and an extraordinary gain of Pounds 26m from the sale
of its Thomas Cook travel agent subsidiary. It did not make a dividend
payment to HSBC last year.
It will add Pounds 242m to HSBC's 1992 profits. This comprises Pounds 89m of
pre-tax profits and Pounds 122m of restructuring costs and a Pounds 31m
permanent diminution in property values which it took as losses, but which
will be charged against HSBC reserves.
The commercial banking division made profits of Pounds 138m against a Pounds
50m loss last year. Its provisions fell 31 per cent to Pounds 557m, although
those on UK corporate and personal loans rose to Pounds 336m in the second
half against Pounds 306m in the first.
The merchant banking division, which includes the Samuel Montagu and
Greenwell Montague stockbrokers businesses, incurred a pre-tax loss of
Pounds 33m (from Pounds 34m profit). This was due to a bad debt charge of
Pounds 77m, created by a few problem accounts.
Mr Brian Pearse, chief executive, said the bank was starting to see
'glimmers of light' from increased economic activity. Midland would gain
from HSBC's strong capital, he said, and from being able to offer corporate
customers access to services such as treasury operations and trade finance
in which it had joined forces with HSBC.
Midland's Firstdirect telephone banking subsidiary did not achieve an
operating profit, because of a high level of spending on advertising. Mr
Pearse said he expected the business to enter operating profit this year.
Overseas commercial banking operations recorded a loss before exceptional
items of Pounds 6m (down from a Pounds 38m profit). Operating income from
overseas offices fell 14 per cent to Pounds 277m and there were losses in
France and Italy.
Profits from foreign exchange trading increased by Pounds 67m helped by
volatility following Britain's exit from the exchange rate mechanism. Mr
Pearse said this was mostly from commission, although the bank had limited
positions.
Following a property revaluation, the bank charged a Pounds 31m permanent
diminution in value to its profit and loss account, and charged to reserves
a remaining revaluation of Pounds 99m.
The tier 1 ratio strengthened to 5.7 per cent, while the total risk asset
ratio rose to 10.7 per cent (from 10.3 per cent). Total assets rose to
Pounds 61.3bn (from Pounds 59.8bn) and risk-weighted assets rose slightly to
Pounds 41.9bn.
Total operating income excluding Thomas Cook's contribution fell marginally
to Pounds 2.96bn (from Pounds 2.97bn), while total operating expenses fell
to Pounds 2.03bn (from Pounds 2.04bn) and the cost-to-income ratio remained
at 68.6 per cent.
HSBC's 75p ordinary shares closed 23p up at 624p.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
