<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 93 / Water companies warn of high clean-up costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WATER COMPANIES called yesterday for more flexible standards on drinking
water and warned that complete elimination of lead from water could cost
Pounds 8bn.
European countries should have the right to set their own standards on the
colour and taste of drinking water where there were no health implications,
said Ms Janet Langdon, director of the Water Services Association, which
represents the 10 large water and sewerage companies of England and Wales.
The WSA said it accepted the World Health Organisation's tighter guidelines
on lead, which is thought to pose health risks, but warned that much of the
Pounds 8bn cost for removing lead from water would fall on householders. It
also called yesterday for a UK policy on pesticides to reduce the level of
chemicals that run off fields into the water supply and require expensive
removal.
The UK move is part of an attempt by Eureau, a lobby group representing
national water companies from all EC countries except Greece, to persuade
the European Commission to change its water directives. Officials from the
Commission's environment directorate, speaking yesterday at the opening of
Eureau's conference in Madrid, said they wanted to hold a seminar by the
autumn on the need to review the standards.
The drinking water standards, set in 1980, are among the most ambitious
environmental measures passed by EC members and have become increasingly
controversial as the true cost of compliance has become clear. UK companies
have suggested that nearly half of the Pounds 45bn they are likely to invest
this decade will be as a result of EC directives.
Ofwat, the regulator of the UK companies, has repeatedly questioned whether
some of the standards are unnecessary and too stringent.
The European water companies want limits on the levels of iron, magnesium,
manganese, copper and zinc, which they argue have no impact on health, to be
interpreted more flexibly by the Commission.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
