<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 93 / Maxwell's Pounds 1/2 m surprise: Son of corrupt tycoon
averts bankruptcy with payment to liquidators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR IAN MAXWELL yesterday avoided the immediate threat of bankruptcy when he
made a last-minute payment of Pounds 500,000 to the liquidators of
Bishopsgate Investment Management, the former manager of the Mirror Group
Newspapers pension funds.
Mr Maxwell had been ordered to pay the money in December after a High Court
judge ruled that he had breached his duty as a BIM director by agreeing to
the transfer of shares worth about Pounds 580,000 to Credit Suisse without
obtaining an assurance that the BIM board had approved the transfer.
The bankruptcy proceedings were set in motion after Mr Maxwell's lawyers
indicated that he could not afford the interim payment.
However, five minutes before yesterday's bankruptcy hearing was due to
start, Mr Maxwell handed over a banker's draft for Pounds 500,000 to Miss
Margaret Cole of Stephenson Harwood, the solicitors acting for BIM. He also
agreed to pay the substantial legal costs of bringing the bankruptcy
proceedings against him. He then left without waiting for formal dismissal
of the bankruptcy petition. His payment of the money prompted speculation
about the origin of the funds and the apparent change in his financial
circumstances.
Mr Frank Field, chairman of the House of Commons social security committee
which is investigating the Maxwell affair, said the 'magic' production of
the money came as no surprise. 'Whenever the Maxwells have been in
difficulty money has arrived,' he said.
Mr John Clitheroe of Kingsley Napley, Mr Maxwell's solicitor, refused to
comment on the source of the money but said: 'Ill-informed speculation on
these matters is a pity.' Miss Cole said the money would go into the fund
for the benefit of Mirror Group pensioners. But Mr Kenneth Trench, chairman
of the Maxwell Pensioners' Action Group, said the payment was 'really
disappointing' and would yield only a minute sum for each pensioner.
The liquidators would continue their claim against Mr Maxwell for the
outstanding balance of Pounds 80,000, plus interest since September 1991,
she said. They would also consider the position regarding their outstanding
claim against Mr Maxwell for more than Pounds 400m.
</TEXT>
