<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 93 / East Midlands business leaders want government spending to
be maintained in real terms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Business leaders in the east Midlands want government spending to be at
least maintained in real terms, and believe that any increase should be
financed by extending the scope of value added tax.
A poll of 100 executives by Price Waterhouse, the accountancy firm, found
most wanted higher government spending on transport and capital
infrastructure, but lower spending on social security benefits.
The survey of business opinion in Derbyshire, Leicestershire, Lincolnshire,
Northamptonshire and Nottinghamshire was published yesterday.
The business leaders are anxious that Mr Lamont should extend indefinitely
the temporary increase, announced in the last Autumn Statement, of capital
allowances for plant, machinery and industrial buildings.
