<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 93 / Heseltine backs export drive in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, yesterday lent his
support to the launch of one of Britain's most ambitious export promotion
campaigns, in spite of criticism that it is poorly timed.
The campaign, North America Now, is aimed at reversing a long decline in
Britain's share of the US market and at forging joint ventures for
medium-sized companies. But
it comes as a new US administration is drawing up potentially protectionist
trade policies.
Mr Heseltine said the campaign's timing could not be better. Sterling's
devaluation had boosted opportunities for exporters, and there was clear
evidence that the US and Canada were emerging strongly from recession.
The Pounds 1.8m three-year campaign comes after five years in which the
European single market has been the main focus of Britain's export promotion
strategy.
No formal target has been set, but the government hopes the UK share of US
visible imports can be lifted from 3.8 per cent to 5 per cent by 1995,
boosting exports in money terms by about Pounds 3bn a year from the current
Pounds 12.2bn.
The campaign has several innovative features including the targeting of 20
US sectors with 50 events planned in north America over six months; nine
'export promoters' seconded to the DTI from the private sector will work
with prospective exporters as part of the campaign; there will be an
education programme including 10 scholarships a year at the JL Kellogg
School of Management in Chicago and workshops on issues such as US sales
practices and how to reduce market entry overhead costs; and a 'big
companies partnership' will be created involving discussions with leading
exporters to the US on where the government can assist in overcoming trade
barriers, or in defining how US trade and investment fits into the
companies' growth strategy.
Regional initiatives will range from backing a partnership between the oil
regions around Calgary and Aberdeen to a sectoral initiative between Wales
and Ontario, and an 'America Week' in Birmingham this month to coincide with
British Airways' inaugural direct flight to New York.
Another element in the campaign is the appointment of Price Waterhouse, the
accountancy and management consultancy group, to work with 50 medium-sized
companies a year with the aim of forging 'strategic partnerships' in the US.
The aim is to introduce each company to up to three prospective US partners.
It is hoped to set up 10 to 15 partnerships each year over the three years
of the campaign, generating earnings towards the UK balance of payments
amounting to Pounds 30m.
'These companies will not be beginners,' said Mr Ian Guthrie, partner at
Price Waterhouse responsible for the project. 'They should have between 100
and 500 staff, a turnover of Pounds 10m-Pounds 50m, and a good foothold in
the US market already. They will be companies that have put serious time
into export promotion as part of a clear business plan.'
</TEXT>
