<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 93 / Midlands attracts advice shops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT plans to set up a network of one-stop business advice centres
have taken off better in some parts of the country than in others.
If the locations of the business partnerships applying to run the centres is
reflected in eventual contract awards, there will be a disproportionately
large number of 'one-stop shops' in the Midlands and the north of England.
The response in the south and the south-west has been less strong. Most of
the partnerships are led by Training and Enterprise Councils, the
employer-led bodies that deliver government training schemes in England and
Wales.
Interviews to select 15 pilot outlets, announced last December by Mr Michael
Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, will begin shortly. The DTI has
received a total of 57 applications.
Mr Heseltine hopes the shops, which will eventually number 200, will
revolutionise support for British companies.
The outlets will bring together the business services of chambers of
commerce, local authorities, local enterprise agencies and the DTI.
Mr Heseltine has allocated Pounds 3.5m for the 'one-stop shops' from the
Tecs' budgets and the government hopes that the services, many of which are
now free, will be charged for.
Mr Heseltine was asked in the Commons last year whether the pilots would be
spread to represent regions of high business failures. He replied that the
basis for choosing the successful bids would be 'one of quality'.
The UK has received more US overseas direct investment since 1987 than any
other country, a study said yesterday.
Some 21 per cent of US overseas investment came to the UK, which also
received 9 per cent of Japanese overseas direct investment, ahead of any
country except the US.
The study, by the Centre for Economics and Business Research on behalf of
the CBI, shows that nearly a fifth of the Pounds 220bn invested in British
industry since 1987 came from abroad.
</TEXT>
