<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 93 / Minister warns about navy order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE and DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JONATHAN Aitken, the defence procurement minister, was warned yesterday
about the future of Swan Hunter. The Tyneside shipbuilder, which has a blank
order book after next year, is dependent on its bid for a Ministry of
Defence helicopter carrier - a Pounds 170m order which may be shelved
because of financial pressures on the defence budget.
Mr Aitken, who was visiting Swan Hunter to see work in progress, said that
the government, now studying bids for the Landing Platform Helicopter
vessel, had taken the carrier into account in drawing up its future defence
budget. However, he he warned that a final decision depended on available
resources.
He added: 'No minister can give a guarantee but we are proceeding in good
faith.'
A decision will be made by the autumn. Without the order Swan Hunter, now
reducing its workforce by 1,400 to 2,200, looks set to close.
Campaigning by management, unions and Tyneside MPs has left ministers well
aware of the impact that the closure of Swan Hunter would have on Tyneside's
economy and morale.
Britain has made preliminary contacts with Canada on the possible transfer
of the Royal Navy's latest diesel-powered patrol submarines, David White
writes.
The move would be part of a plan to find equipment savings to match the
Pounds 1bn cut decided last November in the UK defence budget over the next
two financial years. The four new Upholder class submarines have cost the
MoD about Pounds 800m.
The defence ministry said yesterday no decision had been taken on whether to
dispose of them.
According to the magazine Jane's Defence Weekly, Canada would favour a
leasing arrangement while the UK would prefer an outright sale.
The last of the submarines, HMS Unicorn, built at the VSEL group's Cammell
Laird in Birkenhead, is undergoing trials. Under its Options for Change
programme, the MoD decided against building any more of the boats.
</TEXT>
