<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 93 / Observer: Sizing up
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
What's so special about the Halifax Building Society? It hasn't had an
exciting public flotation like the Abbey National or been as profitable as
the Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester.
Hence, there will be some pained expressions at Halifax HQ at the sight of a
25 per cent jump in Abbey National's assets to Pounds 71.8bn. True, the
Abbey is no longer a building society and its balance sheet has been
inflated by money market activities. But unless there has been some nifty
end-year window-dressing, it would be surprising if the Halifax balance
sheet is bigger than the Abbey's when it reports in a fortnight's time.
Take no notice of Halifax if it says that size doesn't matter any more.
Being the biggest was one of its few claims to fame.
