<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 93 / Rise in tendering 'would cut costs'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GREATER use of competitive tendering would reduce the cost and improve the
quality of public services, the Institute of Economic Affairs says in a
report published today, John Willman writes.
The think tank says local and central government organisations continue to
place obstacles before companies which might bid for contracts. It
identifies scope to extend competitive tendering in local government, fire
services and some police work.
The report says the rule which excludes tendering of activities worth less
than Pounds 100,000 a year should be examined to see if the limit could be
lowered.
Testing the Market. IEA, 2 Lord North Street, London SW1P 3LB. Pounds 16.
